In java, really only `int`, `double`, `float`, `long`, and `boolean` are the true primitives. `short`, `char`, and `byte` are inferior half-non-existent types.

You can create arrays of them (`byte[]` exists), and use them as a type (`byte a;` is legal), but in math operations __there is no such thing as a byte, short, or char__.

Given:

```
byte a = 5;
byte b = 10;
```

The expression `a + b` is of type int. As in, if you try this stunt:

```
public void test(int a) {
  System.out.println(&quot;The int variant&quot;);
}

public void test(byte a) {
  System.out.println(&quot;The byte variant&quot;);
}

byte x = 5;
byte y = 10;
test(x + y);
```

You would see... &quot;The int variant&quot;.

To do what you want to do here, add casts to `byte`: `byte b = (byte) (a &lt;&lt; 2);`.


NB: In Bytecode, i.e. the stuff in class files; what `javac` makes for you, bytes, booleans, shorts, and floats do not exist at all. There&#39;s `DADD`, `FADD`, `IADD`, and `LADD` (for double/float/int/long respectively). There are no short, char, or byte variants.

The reason is fairly simple: Given that CPUs when java was created were almost all at least 32-bit (and in fact, today, almost all are 64-bit), you gain absolutely nothing whatsoever by using fewer bits; if anything, it would be _slower_, not faster.

Java &#39;correctly&#39; packs byte arrays (each entry in a byte array only takes 8 bits, not more). That&#39;s the only time where &#39;... but bytes are small!&#39; is relevant, and java does the correct thing there.

